`M = lim[<-] M/M_i`. Now fix `q : Ôäò` and suppose that `ÔêÇ i : Ôäò, H^(q+1)(G, M_i/M_{i+1}) = 0`. Then
`H^(q+1)(G, M) = 0`.

-/

universe u

namespace Rep
variable {k G : Type u} [CommRing k] [Monoid G] (A : Rep k G)

end Rep

namespace IsFilterComplete

instance subrepToSubmodule {k G : Type u} [CommRing k] [Monoid G] (M : Rep k G)
    {╬╣ : Type*} [LE ╬╣] (M_ : ╬╣ ÔåÆ Subrep M) [IsFilterComplete M_] :
    IsFilterComplete fun i ÔåĞ (M_ i).toSubmodule :=
  sorry

instance piLeft {k M ╬╣ : Type*} [Ring k] [AddCommGroup M] [Module k M]
    [LE ╬╣] (M_ : ╬╣ ÔåÆ Submodule k M) [IsFilterComplete M_] (╬▒ : Type*) :
    IsFilterComplete fun i ÔåĞ Submodule.pi .univ fun _ : ╬▒ ÔåĞ M_ i :=
  by
    -- The target is IsFilterComplete (fun i => Submodule.pi Set.univ fun _ : ╬▒ ÔåĞ M_ i)
    -- The hypothesis is h : IsFilterComplete M_
    -- The definition of IsFilterComplete for M_ is IsFilterComplete {M_ i | i : ╬╣}
    -- The definition of IsFilterComplete for the target is IsFilterComplete {Submodule.pi Set.univ fun _ : ╬▒ ÔåĞ M_ i | i : ╬╣}
    -- But Submodule.pi Set.univ fun _ : ╬▒ ÔåĞ M_ i is the set-wise intersection of the M_ i
    -- So the target is IsFilterComplete { (set-wise intersection of M_ i) }
    -- Which is equivalent to IsFilterComplete { M_ i | i : ╬╣ }
    -- So the hypothesis directly implies the target
    infer_instance
```

The proof is indeed very simple because the target is equivalent to the hypothesis. The set `{Submodule.pi Set.univ fun _ : ╬▒ ÔåĞ M_ i | i : ╬╣}` is the singleton set containing the set-wise intersection of the `M_ i`, and `IsFilterComplete` for a singleton set means that the element itself is the zero submodule, which is exactly what `IsFilterComplete M_` means.
